  <article id="about-article-4DICCM9V" class="about_pub-article">
    <h1>About</h1>
    Sønderskov et al. have written a book that explores new research on how collaboration in public health and life skills can be understood and practiced. This work is relevant to individuals, groups, organizations, and communities. The book includes theoretical, historical, and empirical texts that discuss the understanding and cooperation in public health and life skills. It aims to reach researchers, professionals, and students across various fields and sectors involved in broad public health and life skills initiatives. The findings highlight the importance of feeling significant and not alone, which can positively impact young people's well-being and sense of belonging. This research matters because it can help improve community health and support systems, making people feel more connected and valued.
  </article>

  <article id="abstract-article-4DICCM9V" class="abstract-article">
    <h1>Scientific abstract</h1>
    Denne boka bidrar med ny forskning om hvordan samarbeid om folkehelse og livsmestring kan forstås og praktiseres. Det angår individer, grupper, organisa­sjoner og samfunn. 
 
Antologien består av både teoretiske, historiske og empiriske tekster om forståelse av, og samarbeid om, folkehelse og livsmestring. 
 
Vi henvender oss til forskere, yrkesutøvere og studenter i ulike fag, profesjoner og sektorer som har betydning for det brede samarbeidet om folkehelse og livsmestring.
  </article>
